</div></div></div></div><div id="sage-summary-section" class="cs-summary__section"><div class="cs-summary__card"><div class="cs-summary__label">Case Study Summary</div><p class="cs-summary__text">As product designer for Sortly's AI assistant, I tackled a chatbot whose answers were accurate but trapped in a full-page container that fought the user. I redesigned Sage into a persistent, collapsible sidekick with in-product ticketing, which doubled Sage-handled resolutions and cut agent-handled support tickets by 29%.</p></div></div><div id="sage-problem-section" class="sage-problem-section"><div class="inline-div-2-1"><div class="div-block-367"><div class="inline-div-0-1">Problem</div><p class="inline-p-0-1">The off-the-shelf bot was failing. The dev team replaced it with a quick-and-dirty full-page beta: no thoughtful UI, no UX, just a proof of concept using our help center documentation plus Claude Sonnet to validate response quality. At 10% of users, it outperformed the old bot. Good enough to ship. Not good enough to use.</p></div><div class="div-block-368"><div class="inline-div-1-1">How could I build a chatbot experience that made Sage genuinely useful for the questions it could answer, without leaving users or the CX team feeling abandoned by it?</div></div></div></div><div id="sage-process-section" class="sage-process-section"><div class="inline-div-27"><div class="div-block-366"><div class="inline-div-0-1-2">Process</div><p class="inline-p-0-1-2">I started with the full-page experience and immediately hit the fundamental problem: for &quot;How to&quot; questions, Sage was returning accurate, step-by-step instructions. But users couldn&#x27;t follow those steps while staying in an open dialogue. They had to choose between reading Sage&#x27;s answer and doing the thing Sage was describing. Most opened a second browser window. Some just closed the chat.</p></div><div class="inline-div-13"><div class="inline-div-12"><div class="inline-div-1-1-2"></div><div class="inline-div-2-1-2"><span class="inline-span-0-1">V1</span><span class="inline-span-1-1">Full Page Experience</span><span class="inline-span-2-1">Sage as a destination</span></div><div class="inline-div-11"><div class="inline-div-6"><div class="inline-div-3-1-2">Isolated component</div><div class="inline-div-5"><img src="/assets/cs/sage/69f9433cfcd90fe574300751_Image_1.png" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 820px) 100vw, 820px" srcset="/assets/cs/sage/69f9433cfcd90fe574300751_Image_1-p-500.png 500w, /assets/cs/sage/69f9433cfcd90fe574300751_Image_1-p-800.png 800w, /assets/cs/sage/69f9433cfcd90fe574300751_Image_1.png 820w" alt="Chat interface with greeting &#x27;Hey Emily! How can I help?&#x27; and a text input field with placeholder &#x27;Type your question here&#x27; plus three example question buttons: &#x27;How do I move items?&#x27;, &#x27;Can I create Invoices?&#x27; and &#x27;How do I print barcode labels?&#x27;" class="image-170"/></div><p class="inline-p-1">This was the V1 greeting screen — shown once, the first time a user opened Sage. Once they started a prompt and returned, the full page experience took over and they never saw it again.</p></div><div class="inline-div-10"><div class="inline-div-7">In context</div><div class="inline-div-9"><img src="/assets/cs/sage/69f9433cc6db972f3657b6d5_Image_2.png" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" srcset="/assets/cs/sage/69f9433cc6db972f3657b6d5_Image_2-p-500.png 500w, /assets/cs/sage/69f9433cc6db972f3657b6d5_Image_2-p-800.png 800w, /assets/cs/sage/69f9433cc6db972f3657b6d5_Image_2.png 1024w" alt="Sortly Sage app interface showing workflow setup instructions, with menu on left and cards for guides on organizing inventory." class="image-169"/></div><p class="inline-p-2">When a response had supporting content — help articles, videos, or gifs related to the prompt — it surfaced as a list in the chat thread. In V0 this was a list view that was very hard for users to see and navigate.</p></div></div></div></div><p class="inline-p-3">We tracked closely through Amplitude: what users asked, what they did after. Two patterns became undeniable: users needed to navigate Sortly while talking to Sage, not instead of it , and when Sage couldn&#x27;t resolve an issue, they were being pushed out of the product to file a Zendesk ticket, re-entering information (email, username, company ID) that Sortly already had.</p><p class="inline-p-4">Version 1 was the full-page experience. Accurate responses, wrong container. Version 2 introduced a collapsible chat window. Better, but the ticket submission path still kicked users out of the product. CX stakeholders needed an in-product ticket flow; getting engineering alignment required surfacing the user cost of making someone re-enter their own account information to ask for help.</p><div class="inline-div-26"><div class="inline-div-25"><div class="inline-div-14"></div><div class="inline-div-15"><span class="inline-span-3">V2</span><span class="inline-span-4">Collapsible Drawer</span><span class="inline-span-5">Sage as a sidekick</span></div><div class="inline-div-24"><div class="inline-div-19"><div class="inline-div-16">In context</div><div class="inline-div-18"><img src="/assets/cs/sage/69f9433c9211f6317a029cfe_Image_3.png" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" srcset="/assets/cs/sage/69f9433c9211f6317a029cfe_Image_3-p-500.png 500w, /assets/cs/sage/69f9433c9211f6317a029cfe_Image_3-p-800.png 800w, /assets/cs/sage/69f9433c9211f6317a029cfe_Image_3.png 1024w" alt="Inventory management interface showing folders and items with a chatbot assistant named Sage offering common question options." class="image-171"/></div><p class="inline-p-5">We expanded the FAQs section based on the questions users asked most in V1. The collapsed nav keeps the app fully accessible — no context switch required.</p></div><div class="inline-div-23"><div class="inline-div-20">In context</div><div class="inline-div-22"><img src="/assets/cs/sage/69f9433c2802a4e7ed2aa38f_Image_4.png" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" srcset="/assets/cs/sage/69f9433c2802a4e7ed2aa38f_Image_4-p-500.png 500w, /assets/cs/sage/69f9433c2802a4e7ed2aa38f_Image_4-p-800.png 800w, /assets/cs/sage/69f9433c2802a4e7ed2aa38f_Image_4.png 1024w" alt="Inventory management interface with folders and items list on the left and a chat window on the right showing support conversation and resource links." class="image-172"/></div><p class="inline-p-6">When Sage can&#x27;t resolve an issue, the ticket is filed directly in the drawer — chat history attached, no product exit.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div><div id="sage-solution-section" class="sage-solution-section"><div class="inline-div-2-1-2-3"><div class="inline-div-0-1-2-3">Solution</div><p class="inline-p-0-1-2-3">Sage became a sidekick, not a destination. Users can open it from anywhere in the product, follow instructions without losing the thread, and submit a support ticket without re-entering information we already have. The full-page experience was retired.</p><p class="inline-p-1-1">The solution that shipped was a persistent, collapsible Sage window accessible from any screen, with a direct ticket submission screen pre-populated with account data. Sage got a name, a brand identity (the owl icon), cards for external links and how-to videos, and a layout built to scale down to mobile from day one.</p></div></div><div id="sage-outcomes-section" class="sage-outcomes-section"><div id="sage-outcomes-content" class="sage-outcomes-content"><div class="inline-div-0-1-2-3-4">Outcomes</div><p class="inline-p-0-1-2-3-4">Once we started to see the results, the numbers didn&#x27;t lie.</p><div id="sage-outcomes-grid" class="sage-outcomes-grid"><div class="inline-div-3-1-2-3-4"><div id="sage-outcome-solves" data-prefix="+" data-target="44" data-suffix="%" class="inline-div-1-1-2-3-4">+44%</div><div class="inline-div-2-1-2-3-4">Sage-handled solves</div></div><div class="inline-div-6-1"><div id="sage-outcome-agent-tickets" data-prefix="-" data-target="29" data-suffix="%" class="inline-div-4-1-2">−29%</div><div class="inline-div-5-1">Agent-handled tickets</div></div><div class="inline-div-9-1"><div id="sage-outcome-zendesk-tickets" data-prefix="-" data-target="15" data-suffix="%" class="inline-div-7-1">−15%</div><div class="inline-div-8-1">Zendesk-handled tickets</div></div><div class="inline-div-12-1"><div id="sage-outcome-trial-tickets" data-prefix="-" data-target="48" data-suffix="%" class="inline-div-10-1">−48%</div><div class="inline-div-11-1">Trial tickets in August</div></div></div><div id="sage-outcomes-footnote" class="inline-div-14-1">Steepest single-month trial ticket decline in over a year · Zendesk bot fully sunsetted January 2026</div></div><div id="sage-channel-chart-placeholder" class="sage-channel-chart-placeholder"><div class="w-embed"><!-- ── Outcomes + Solves by Channel (tinted) ─────────────────────────────────── -->
<div class="band band--tinted outcomes-band reveal">
  <div class="chart-wrap chart-wrap--card">
    <svg id="chart-channel" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" style="display: block; width: 100%; max-width: 920px; margin: 0 auto"></svg>
  </div>
</div></div></div></div><div id="sage-analysis-section" class="sage-analysis-section"><div class="inline-div-1-1-2-3-4-5"><div class="inline-div-0-1-2-3-4-5">Analysis</div></div><p class="inline-p-0-1-2-3-4-5">As the chatbot window gained more users, I kept tracking not just resolution rates but what Sage was actually handling. Each week I reviewed the conversations: what users asked, how Sage responded, where the answers were accurate. This is a representative week from December 2025 threads all resolved without agent handoff.</p><div id="sage-topic-chart-placeholder" class="sage-topic-chart-placeholder"><div class="code-embed-2 w-embed"><div class="chart-wrap">
  <svg id="chart-topics" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" style="display: block; width: 100%; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto"></svg>
</div></div></div><p class="inline-p-1-1-2">Sage wasn&#x27;t perfect. The LLM occasionally fabricated instructions, and users would follow steps that were incomplete or flat-out wrong. Those failures were useful: they exposed gaps in the help center documentation, and fixing Sage&#x27;s errors made the source material more accurate than it had been before Sage existed.</p></div><div id="sage-retrospective-footer-section" class="sage-retrospective-footer-section"><div id="sage-retrospective-section" class="sage-retrospective-section"><div class="inline-div-1-1-2-3-4-5-6"><div class="inline-div-0-1-2-3-4-5-6">Retrospective</div><p class="inline-p-0-1-2-3-4-5-6">The hardest advocacy win was the ticket submission feature. Engineering saw it as scope; the CX team needed it; users were paying the cost of its absence every time they left the product to file a ticket. Getting alignment required making that cost visible with data, not just logic.</p><p class="inline-p-1-1-2-3">With more time, I would have started this project 6–12 months earlier. The dev team&#x27;s &quot;quick and dirty&quot; validation phase was necessary, but it ran longer than it needed to because the UX work wasn&#x27;t parallel to the quality validation. Sage could have reached its current form sooner.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="sage-scripts" class="code-embed-3 w-embed w-script"><!-- ── Chart: Solves by Channel ──────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<script is:inline>
(function() {
  const NS = 'http://www.w3.org/2000/svg';
  const W=920, H=458, ML=52, MR=28, MT=90, MB=100;
  const PW=W-ML-MR, PH=H-MT-MB, YB=MT+PH;
  const BAR_W=36, STEP=56, N=15;
  const BX0=ML+(PW-(N*BAR_W+(N-1)*20))/2;
  const SCALE=PH/100;
  const C={
    sage:'#046c7a',sageBg:'#e8f6f7',
